          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">
          Yunus has doubts</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: The political friction in Bangladesh made Muhammad Yunus reconsider his role. </strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Muhammad Yunus, Bangladesh's interim leader, may resign <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-spotlight-h2-2-due-to-political-chaos" target="_blank">due to political chaos</a> and a lack of party support. He feels frustrated that political groups cannot reach common ground, complicating the process. The 84-year-old demands full support from the political parties and wants to work independently. The ongoing protests embarrass the Nobel Laureate and assert that he can't work well in the current environment. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        His frustration <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-spotlight-h2-3-grows-with-large-protests" target="_blank">grows with large protests</a> from the center-right Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP), which demands a clear election plan. The BNP‚Äôs threat to withdraw support from Yunus‚Äô government adds to the tension. Bangladesh is also dealing with extremism. Since the ousting of the last PM, previously banned militant groups have regrouped. Homes have been set on fire, and ethnic Hindus <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-spotlight-h2-4-are-facing-violence" target="_blank">are facing violence</a> despite Yunus‚Äôs promises for equality.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Following an unscheduled, closed-door council meeting, Planning Advisor Wahiduddin Mahmud told reporters that Yunus had expressed <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-spotlight-h2-5-no-intention-to-step-down" target="_blank">no intention to step down</a>. The council met shortly after the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-spotlight-h2-6-ecnec-session" target="_blank">ECNEC session</a>. Political friction has recently grown between the student-led National Citizen Party (NCP) and the BNP. BNP wants student representatives out of the cabinet, while NCP has accused two advisers of favoring BNP interests.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Key adviser Syeda Rizwana Hasan insisted that the interim government‚Äôs mission included bringing reform, restoring justice, and conducting the election. Bangladesh‚Äôs 170Mn citizens wait for peace amid protests and competing demands. </p>
        </mj-text>
