     How do the US crackdowns on‚Äå Ivy League universities affect US-Chinese relations?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/declining-us-college-appeal-chinese-students-trend.jpg" alt="A US college education, once a status symbol for Chinese families, appears to be losing its appeal" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>A US college education, once a status symbol for Chinese families, appears to be losing its appeal. Credits: Xinhua/Li Muzi</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        The Trump Administration‚Äôs crackdown on Ivy League schools has some implications for US-China relations. While less severe than the tariff wars, the US uses its prestigious Ivy League universities as a mode of soft power. Harvard University‚Äôs ties with China, including research partnerships and student exchanges, have become problematic due to rising US-China tensions. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Hong Kong‚Äôs Education Secretary, Christine Choi, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-foundations-h1-14-discussed-how-rising" target="_blank">discussed how rising</a> tensions between the US and China affect mainland Chinese students. She cites that uncertainty over US policies, including visa revocations and strict immigration rules, could lead more students to opt for studying in Hong Kong. Choi noted a decline in Hong Kong students choosing to go to the US for education.</p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The Trump administration <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-foundations-h1-15-accused-harvard" target="_blank">accused Harvard</a> of allowing Chinese Communist Party influence on campus. They claimed the university worked with Beijing and permitted antisemitism and political harassment. Experts say that while Chinese influence might be an issue, banning international students isn‚Äôt the answer. Chinese nationals <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-26-may-25-foundations-h1-16-made-up-about-20" target="_blank">made up about 20%</a> of Harvard's foreign intake in 2024. </p>
